06295nam a22008895i 9783110627176DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020943768  a97831106271767 a10.1515/97831106271762doi  a(DE-B1597)501431  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0400302bisacsh02aA Touch of Doubt :bOn Haptic Scepticism /ced. by Rachel Aumiller. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (V, 220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies and Texts in Scepticism ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tSensation & Hesitation: Haptic Scepticism as an Ethics of Touching -- t"Es wird Leib, es empfindet": Auto-Affection, Doubt, and the Philosopher's Hands -- tWhen to Touch and What to Doubt: Zeroing In on the Tactile Surplus -- tThe (Un)Touchable Touch of Pyramus and Thisbe: Doubt and Desire -- tA Magic Touch: Performative Haptic Acts in Biblical and Medieval Jewish Magic -- tNoli me tangere: The Profaning Touch That Challenges Authority -- tTouching Doubt: Haptolinguistic Scepticism -- tAn Atom of Touch: Scepticism from Hegel to Lacan -- tThe Weak Relations of Touch and Sight through the Passage of Lapsed Time -- tList of Contributors -- tList of Figures -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhat can we know about ourselves and the world through the sense of touch and what are the epistemic limits of touch? Scepticism claims that there is always something that slips through the epistemologist's grasp. A Touch of Doubt explores the significance of touch for the history of philosophical scepticism as well as for scepticism as an embodied form of subversive political, religious, and artistic practice. Drawing on the tradition of scepticism within nineteenth- and twentieth-century continental philosophy and psychoanalysis, this volume discusses how the sense of touch uncovers contradictions within our knowledge of ourselves and the world. It questions 1) what we can know through touch, 2) what we can know about touch itself, and 3) how our experience of touching the other and ourselves throws us into a state of doubt. This volume is intended for students and scholars who wish to reconsider the experience of touching in intersections of philosophy, religion, art, and social and political practice.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aIdealismus. 4aPhilosophie der Psychoanalyse. 4aSkeptizismus. 4apostmoderne Philosophie. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aGerman idealism.  aScepticism.  acontinental philosophy.  apostmodern philosophy.1 aAumiller, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAumiller, Rachel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHayon, Adi Louria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolenc, Bara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomel, Mirt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfaller, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPisano, Libera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRebiger, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVranešević, Goran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaftefunder.4fnd4htt